properties.documentation: This package contains all model elements part of the language's Abstract Syntax, Concrete Syntax, and Semantics specification.

This package contains the views, entities, and relationships of the language in a notation compliant to the Meta-Object Facility metamodeling standard by the OMG. Therefore, it contains information needed to specify the languages vocabulary and grammar
This package contains all entities and relationships which map to the language's stereotypes in an implementation via an UML profile.

This package contains information about the tailored representation of entities, and relationships of the language in a notation compliant to the Meta-Object Facility metamodeling standard by the OMG. Therefore, it contains information how language should be represented (e.g. plaintext or graphical symbols).

This package contains a recommended hierarchical base structure for creating elements for specifying representations of the language's elements. Furthermore, it contains enumerations related to these base class'es attributes to define valid values of attributes to specify the concrete syntax of elements.
A Concrete Syntax Element contains the main properties needed to describe parameters of the appearance of an ASM element.
A Concrete Syntax Class contains the main properties needed to describe parameters of the appearance of an ASM class-like element.
A Concrete Syntax Relationship contains the main properties needed to describe parameters of the appearance of an ASM relation-like element.

documentation.value: (RGB) Red, green, blue. e.g. 0,0,0 -> black 255,255,255 -> white
Red, green, blue, alpha. Same as rgb, but additional value for transparency

properties.documentation: This package contains elements directly imported from the uml 2.5.1 specification in XMI-format provided by the omg (https://www.omg.org/spec/UML/2.5.1/). These serve as base types for implementing the language and are extended with custom stereotypes to create new elements that are tailored to the specified domain-specific language. Using the exact same elements as in the standard for extending these base types provides traceability and consistency across language specification models.

A link is a tuple of values that refer to typed objects. An Association classifies a set of links, each of which is an instance of the Association. Each value in the link refers to an instance of the type of the corresponding end of the Association.

documentation.value: Specifies whether the Association is derived from other model elements such as other Associations.
endType is derived from the types of the member ends.

properties.documentation: A Class classifies a set of objects and specifies the features that characterize the structure and behavior of those objects. A Class may have an internal structure and Ports.

documentation.value: If true, the Class does not provide a complete declaration and cannot be instantiated. An abstract Class is typically used as a target of Associations or Generalizations.
Determines whether an object specified by this Class is active or not. If true, then the owning Class is referred to as an active Class. If false, then such a Class is referred to as a passive Class.

properties.documentation: # Diagram Note This diagram contains elements directly imported from the uml 2.5.1 specification in XMI-format provided by the omg (https://www.omg.org/spec/UML/2.5.1/). These serve as base types for implementing the language and are extended with custom stereotypes to create new elements that are tailored to the specified domain-specific language.
